Use the standard library
This is how to separate_paren_groups of paren_string:
   Remember that groups is []
   Remember that current is ""
   Remember that depth is 0
   Remember that n is paren_string's length
   Remember that i is 0
   Do this n times:
      Remember that c is item i in paren_string
      When c is 40, then:
         Add current to c
         Increase depth
      End when
      When c is 41, then:
         Add current to c
         Decrease depth
         When depth is 0, then:
            Add groups to current
            Remember that current is ""
         End when
      End when
      Increase i
   End do
   The answer is groups
Now you know
>>> separate_paren_groups of [40, 32, 41, 32, 40, 40, 32, 41, 41, 32, 40, 40, 32, 41, 40, 32, 41, 41]
[[40, 41], [40, 40, 41, 41], [40, 40, 41, 40, 41, 41]]
>>> separate_paren_groups of "(()()) ((())) () ((())()())"
["(()())", "((()))", "()", "((())()())"]
>>> separate_paren_groups of "() (()) ((())) (((())))"
["()", "(())", "((()))", "(((())))"]